television auteur. Using key source material, with exclusive access to drafts of many of the episodes across Whedon’s career, as well as unique correspondence with Whedon collaborator Jane Espenson, this book offers unparalleled access to the creative process that helped produce the series Buffy the Vampire Slayer, Angel, Dollhouse and Firefly. Energetic, engaging and informed by detailed scholarship and theoretical rigour, the book is not just an essential addition to the study of Whedon, but a timely and important re-invigoration of television studies in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFantasy comic books, strips, etczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy comic books, strips, etc.zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy television programszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAngel.  aBuffy.  aDollhouse.  aDr. Horrible.  aEspenson.  aFeminism.  aFirefly.  aGenre.  aNarrative.  aWriting.1 aPateman, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614157640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526141576423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526141576/original  a978-3-11-128277-0  Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles